<text>In mathematics, the inverse function of a function (also called the inverse of ) is a function that undoes the operation of . The inverse of exists if and only if is bijective, and if it exists, is denoted by formula_1

For a function formula_2, its inverse formula_3 admits an explicit description: it sends each element formula_4 to the unique element formula_5 such that .

As an example, consider the real-valued function of a real variable given by . One can think of as the function which multiplies its input by 5 then subtracts 7 from the result. To undo this, one adds 7 to the input, then divides the result by 5. Therefore, the inverse of is the function formula_6 defined by formula_7

==Definitions==
Let be a function whose domain is the set , and whose codomain is the set . Then is &quot;invertible&quot; if there exists a function from to such that formula_8 for all formula_5 and formula_10 for all formula_4.

If is invertible, then there is exactly one function satisfying this property. The function is called the inverse of , and is usually denoted as , a notation introduced by John Frederick William Herschel in 1813.

The function is invertible if and only if it is bijective. This is because the condition formula_8 for all formula_5 implies that is injective, and the condition formula_10 for all formula_4 implies that is surjective.

The inverse function to can be explicitly described as the function

:formula_16.

===Inverses and composition===
